DRIVE-THRU FLU SHOT CLINIC in Dalton
is Tuesday, September 22nd!

Dalton, GA – This year’s DRIVE-THRU FLU SHOT CLINIC, conducted by Whitfield County Health Department, is Tuesday, September 22nd from 9 am to 3 pm at the Dalton Convention Center! It’s especially important this year that you’re able to remain separately and safely in your vehicle while driving through to get your flu shot from public health staff wearing COVID-19 protective gear. The shot is no cost if covered by one of several health plans. If paying out of pocket, the cost is still relatively low at $25 for regular flu vaccine and $65 for high dose flu vaccine for people aged 65 and older. Both vaccines guard against 4 different strains of flu. Cash, check, Medicare, Medicaid, Aetna Blue Cross Blue Shield, Cigna, Coventry, Humana and United Healthcare Insurance will be accepted. Dalton Trade and Convention Center is at 2211 Dug Gap Battle Road in Dalton. Call (706) 279-9600 for more information and log onto bit.ly/Drive-Thru_Beat-the-Flu.

post_text:
Improvements Coming to COVID-19 Daily Status Report

Atlanta – Effective Thursday, Sept. 10, at 3 p.m., there will be several improvements to the COVID-19 Daily Status Report on the Georgia Department of Public Health’s (DPH) website. These changes are designed to make the dashboard more user-friendly while providing an accurate picture of COVID-19 in Georgia.

The changes to the Daily Status Report will include:

• Statewide summary statistics are now available below COVID-19 by county map.
• “COVID-19 Over Time” now has the option to zoom in on a specific time period by clicking on the graph and using the mouse to zoom in or out.
• Two new graphs which show cases by age over time, and specifically for children and young adults over time.
• A new graph that shows deaths by age and race.

For updates on COVID-19, follow @GaDPH and @GovKemp on Twitter and @GaDPH and @GovKemp on Facebook.

For information about COVID-19, visit https://dph.georgia.gov/novelcoronavirus or https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/index.html.

post_text:
Please note the attached contact tracing education video in Spanish just released by the Georgia Department of Public Health. This same DPH video in English was shared with you several days ago and is all part of the statewide Answer the Phone campaign that encourages Georgians to respond to contact tracers as they attempt to track and prevent the spread of COVID-19 in our communities. We are seeing an uptick in cases in general in Georgia, but particularly among our Hispanic populations, so please widely share!

Also, please continue to urge social distancing, wearing masks in public, frequent handwashing and getting free COVID-19 testing by public health at locations throughout our health district, including a special clinic tomorrow morning at the Mack Gaston Community Center where we will give away masks and COVID-19 information (click here for info in Spanish or here for English).

People have generally become lax about these measures, and as a result, COVID-19 numbers are increasing.

The Whitfield County Tax Assessors Office is mailing letters this week to Chicken House owners throughout Whitfield County. We are implementing a more accurate and equitable valuation schedule for Chicken House owners. Since various types of poultry houses are valued differently, we need your help providing information on the type of Chicken House you own and operate.
To implement changes for the 2020 digest, we need this information by June 1st. Please call Karen Weeks directly at (706) 275-7421 or by email at kweeks@whitfieldcountyga.com.

post_text:
MORE FREE HAND SANITIZER WEDNESDAY, MAY 6
With hand sanitizer in short supply during the COVID-19 crisis, Dalton Distillery has stepped up to the plate and has been manufacturing hand sanitizer that it is donating to local residents. Company officials Chuck and Raymond Butler asked Commissioner Greg Jones and the Whitfield County Parks and Recreation Department if they would help in the distribution of the hand sanitizer. The company has delivered several batches already, and the latest will be available on Wednesday, May 6 from 9 a.m. to 5 p.m. (or as long as supplies last) at John Davis Recreation Center at 904 Civic Drive, where residents can bring their own bottle (an empty sanitizer bottle or a water bottle will work fine) and dispense 16 ounces of the product. Recreation Director Brian Chastain and other county and city officials expressed thanks to the company for doing its part during this medical crisis. All donations welcome.

The Whitfield County Board of Commissioners have implemented a phased reopening of the County Offices to align ourselves with State and Federal recommendations. While we are not fully operational, we are working hard to get there, while maintaining precautions that serve the best interests of the citizens and employees.

Our Courthouse is still operating under existing judicial orders, however, a few offices have begun to reopen to the public. Please contact the respective department for the operating schedule.

post_text:
MORE FREE HAND SANITIZER TUESDAY, APRIL 28
With hand sanitizer in short supply during the COVID-19 crisis, Dalton Distillery has stepped up to the plate and has been manufacturing hand sanitizer that it is donating to local residents. Company officials Chuck and Raymond Butler asked Commissioner Greg Jones and the Whitfield County Parks and Recreation Department if they would help in the distribution of the hand sanitizer. The company has delivered several batches already, and the latest will be available on Tuesday, April 28 from 8:30 to 5 p.m. (or as long as supplies last) at Edwards Park, where residents can bring their own bottle (an empty sanitizer bottle or a water bottle will work fine) and dispense 16 ounces of the product. Recreation Director Brian Chastain and other county officials expressed thanks to the company for doing its part during this medical crisis.

post_text:
With hand sanitizer in short supply during the COVID-19 crisis, Dalton Distillery has stepped up to the plate and has been manufacturing hand sanitizer that it is donating free to local residents.

Company officials Chuck and Raymond Butler asked Commissioner Greg Jones and the Whitfield County Parks and Recreation Department if they would help in the distribution of the hand sanitizer. Residents can bring their own bottle (an empty sanitizer bottle or a water bottle will work fine) and dispense 16 ounces of the product.

Recreation Director Brian Chastain says the schedule for this week is as follows:

Tuesday, April 14: 9 a.m. to 3 p.m. at Westside Park Miracle Field, 1519 Mount Vernon Road, Rocky Face, GA 30740

Thursday, April 16: 9 a.m. to 3 p.m. at Old Eastbrook Gym, 700 Hill Road, Dalton, Ga 30721

So far, more than 350 gallons have been distributed and more than $1,500 has been donated to Dalton Distillery. "We appreciate all their hard work for the community, and we are glad to partner with them to make sure people have been able to get hand sanitizer!" Chastain said.

COVID-19 Numbers Now Updating Twice Daily

ATLANTA – The number of test results being reported to the Georgia Department of Public Health (DPH) is increasing as more labs are able to test for Covid-19. Additionally, test results are coming in at various times throughout the day from commercial labs. To ensure that the numbers being provided through the COVID-19 data tool on the DPH website, dph.ga.gov, are the most current numbers available, the updates will now be done at NOON and 7 p.m. effective today.

For continued updates on the COVID-19 situation as it develops, follow Georgia Department of Public Health and Governor Brian Kemp on Twitter and Georgia Department of Public Health and Governor Brian Kemp on Facebook.

For information about COVID-19, visit https://dph.georgia.gov/novelcoronavirus or https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/index.html

Kemp, DPH Roll Out Status Report Website for
COVID-19 in Georgia

ATLANTA – Today Governor Kemp and Kathleen E. Toomey, M.D., M.P.H., Georgia Department of Public Health (DPH) commissioner, announced a daily status report page for confirmed COVID-19 cases in Georgia. This will replace nightly news releases from the Governor’s Office and DPH. The report updates every night at midnight to ensure accurate and regular information is provided to the public. The new tool can be found on the DPH website.

For accurate and reliable information about COVID-19 log on to https://dph.georgia.gov/novelcoronavirus or https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/index.html.

post_text: Whitfield County Sheriff’s Office Deputy Jeff Diak received the Law Enforcement Officer of the Year Award 2019-20 from the Georgia American Legion on Feb. 27. Diak, who donated a kidney to fellow Deputy David Headrick in 2019, will now advance to the Southeastern Region competition, where a selection committee will choose the nominee to advance to the National Conference this summer in Louisville, Ky. Attending the awards ceremony were (from left) Headrick, Capt. Clay Pangle, Brittney and Chloe Diak, Jeff Diak, Sheriff Scott Chitwood, and American Legion Post 112 Commander Lee Oliver.
